👉 System:


Email भेजना


Report generate करना


DB backup लेना


Notification भेजना


👉 Requirement:


Tasks schedule करने हैं


Undo support चाहिए


History maintain करनी है


Sender (Scheduler) ≠ Receiver (Service)



❌ Without Pattern (Bad Approach)
class TaskScheduler {

    public void runTask(String type) {
        if (type.equals("EMAIL")) {
            EmailService email = new EmailService();
            email.sendEmail();
        } else if (type.equals("REPORT")) {
            ReportService report = new ReportService();
            report.generateReport();
        } else if (type.equals("BACKUP")) {
            BackupService backup = new BackupService();
            backup.backupDatabase();
        }
    }
}


🚨 Problems (Interview में बोलना जरूरी)
❌ 1. If-Else Hell
👉 हर नया task = नया if-else
❌ 2. Tight Coupling
👉 Scheduler को सब services का पता है
❌ 3. Open-Closed Violation
👉 नया task → existing class modify
❌ 4. No Undo / History
👉 Track नहीं कर सकते
❌ 5. Hard Testing
👉 छोटा change → पूरा system test

✅ Solution: Command Design Pattern
👉 Golden Idea:

“Request को Object बना दो” (Command Object)


🧩 Structure समझो
6

🧱 Step 1: Command Interface
interface TaskCommand {
    void execute();
    void undo();
}


🧱 Step 2: Receiver Classes (Actual Logic)
class EmailService {
    void sendEmail(String msg) {
        System.out.println("Sending Email: " + msg);
    }

    void cancelEmail() {
        System.out.println("Cancelling Email");
    }
}

class ReportService {
    void generateReport() {
        System.out.println("Generating Report");
    }

    void deleteReport() {
        System.out.println("Deleting Report");
    }
}


🧱 Step 3: Concrete Commands
▶️ Email Command
class EmailCommand implements TaskCommand {
    private EmailService service;
    private String message;

    public EmailCommand(EmailService service, String message) {
        this.service = service;
        this.message = message;
    }

    @Override
    public void execute() {
        service.sendEmail(message);
    }

    @Override
    public void undo() {
        service.cancelEmail();
    }
}


▶️ Report Command
class ReportCommand implements TaskCommand {
    private ReportService service;

    public ReportCommand(ReportService service) {
        this.service = service;
    }

    @Override
    public void execute() {
        service.generateReport();
    }

    @Override
    public void undo() {
        service.deleteReport();
    }
}


🧱 Step 4: Invoker (Scheduler)
import java.util.*;

class TaskScheduler {

    Queue<TaskCommand> queue = new LinkedList<>();
    Stack<TaskCommand> history = new Stack<>();

    public void addTask(TaskCommand task) {
        queue.add(task);
    }

    public void runTasks() {
        while (!queue.isEmpty()) {
            TaskCommand task = queue.poll();
            task.execute();
            history.push(task);
        }
    }

    public void undoLast() {
        if (!history.isEmpty()) {
            TaskCommand task = history.pop();
            task.undo();
        }
    }
}


🧪 Usage (Client Code)
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        EmailService emailService = new EmailService();
        ReportService reportService = new ReportService();

        TaskCommand emailTask = new EmailCommand(emailService, "Hello!");
        TaskCommand reportTask = new ReportCommand(reportService);

        TaskScheduler scheduler = new TaskScheduler();

        scheduler.addTask(emailTask);
        scheduler.addTask(reportTask);

        scheduler.runTasks();

        scheduler.undoLast(); // undo last task
    }
}


🎯 Key Concepts (Interview GOLD 🔥)
RoleMeaningCommandInterface (execute, undo)Concrete CommandEmail, ReportReceiverService (actual logic)InvokerSchedulerClientJo command banata hai

🎯 Advantages
✅ 1. Undo/Redo Easy
👉 Stack से history maintain
✅ 2. Decoupling
👉 Sender ≠ Receiver
✅ 3. No If-Else
👉 हर command अलग class
✅ 4. Open-Closed Principle
👉 New command = new class
✅ 5. Flexible
👉 Queue, logging, retry possible

⚠️ Interview Confusion (IMPORTANT)
🔸 Command vs Abstract Factory
CommandAbstract FactoryBehavior focusObject creation focusexecute(), undo()object creationhistory maintainno history

🔸 Command vs Adapter
CommandAdaptertask executionincompatible interface fixundo supportno undo

🔥 Adapter Use Case (Bonus Twist)
👉 Suppose legacy class:
class OldBackup {
    void run() { }
    void undoLast() { }
}

👉 Problem:


Interface expects → execute(), undo()


👉 Solution: Adapter
class BackupAdapter implements TaskCommand {

    private OldBackup backup;

    public BackupAdapter(OldBackup backup) {
        this.backup = backup;
    }

    @Override
    public void execute() {
        backup.run();
    }

    @Override
    public void undo() {
        backup.undoLast();
    }
}


🧠 RATANE KA TARIKA
💡 1 Line याद रखो:

"Command = Request ko object bana do"


🧠 Flow Trick:
Client → Command → Scheduler → Service


🎮 Visual Trick:
👉 Imagine:


Remote = Scheduler 📺


Button = Command 🔘


TV = Receiver 📡


👉 Button दबाओ → Command execute

🔥 Memory Formula:
1. Interface (Command)
2. Concrete Commands
3. Receiver (Logic)
4. Invoker (Scheduler)
5. History (Stack)


🧾 कब Use करें?
✔ Undo / Redo चाहिए
✔ Task history चाहिए
✔ Sender & Receiver decouple करना हो
✔ Queue based execution

🚫 Avoid When
❌ Simple logic (over-engineering)
❌ No undo / history needed
